          "text": "좋다. 이 포지션이면 기존 문서의 축을 더 명확하게 바꿔야 한다.\n\n핵심 수정 방향은 이거다.\n\n- **금융 성과 자랑** 비중 축소\n- **agentic workflows / retrieval / evaluation / reliability** 전면 배치\n- **“혼자 다 했다”**는 남기되, **enterprise-grade 운영 감각**으로 번역\n- **Fieldguide의 키워드**인  \n  - trust  \n  - explainability  \n  - human-in-the-loop  \n  - evaluation / feedback loops  \n  - production reliability  \n  에 맞춰 재서술\n\n그리고 요청대로 **GitHub / Hugging Face / 프로젝트 링크는 전부 살려서** 넣었다.\n\n아래는 **Fieldguide AI Engineer 지원용 영어 경력기술서 개정판**이다.\n\n---\n\n# CAREER PROFILE\n\n## Heewon Oh\n\nGitHub: `https://github.com/unohee`  \nHugging Face: `https://huggingface.co/intrect`  \nOpenSwarm: `https://github.com/unohee/OpenSwarm`  \nkis-agent: `https://github.com/unohee/kis-agent`  \nVELA: `https://huggingface.co/intrect/VELA`  \nSTONKS Demo: `https://stonks.kimkate.net`\n\n---\n\n## Profile\n\nAI-native software engineer with a background spanning machine learning, LLM systems, agent orchestration, retrieval pipelines, and production-facing automation. I specialize in turning ambiguous, judgment-heavy workflows into structured software systems: breaking complex tasks into testable behaviors, integrating LLMs with tools and data sources, and building feedback loops that improve quality over time.\n\nMy work has focused on domains where correctness, traceability, and operational reliability matter. Across LLM applications, retrieval systems, and automation platforms, I have built systems that emphasize transparent reasoning, structured outputs, evaluation loops, and human-usable interfaces rather than raw model novelty alone. fileciteturn1file0L34-L38\n\n---\n\n## Education\n\n**M.A. in Multimedia**  \nDongguk University | 2022\n\n**B.Sc. in Music Computing**  \nGoldsmiths, University of London | 2016 fileciteturn1file0L1-L4\n\n---\n\n## Publications & Research\n\n- *Multidimensional Analysis and Visualization of Audio Datasets*  \n  Journal of Digital Contents Society, Vol. 26 No. 5 (May 2025)\n- *ArtifactNet: AI-Generated Music Detection*  \n  Planned submission to ISMIR 2026\n- Korean patent filed for AI-generated music detection pipeline fileciteturn1file0L5-L10 fileciteturn1file0L41-L56\n\n---\n\n## Professional Experience\n\n**Lecturer, Media Art / Music Programming**  \nSeoul Institute of the Arts | Sep 2021 – Mar 2026\n\n**Lecturer, Music Production**  \nHowon University | Mar 2022 – Jun 2025 fileciteturn1file0L11-L16\n\nIn parallel with teaching, I designed and shipped production-style AI systems as an independent engineer, covering LLM applications, retrieval, backend systems, agent workflows, and model deployment.\n\n---\n\n## Technical Summary\n\n**Languages**  \nPython, JavaScript / Node.js, Bash, SQL\n\n**AI / LLM**  \nPyTorch, Transformers, Unsloth, SFT/DPO fine-tuning, Tool Calling, RAG, FAISS, SBERT, BM25, vLLM, llama-cpp, GGUF/ONNX, TensorRT-LLM, Triton\n\n**Infrastructure / Backend**  \nFastAPI, GraphQL, Docker / OrbStack, Nginx, Redis, SQLite WAL, GitHub Actions, WebSocket\n\n**Deployment / Ops**  \nRunPod Serverless, Cloudflare Tunnel, Tailscale, MLX\n\n**Audio / Research**  \nLibROSA, Demucs, FFmpeg, Max/MSP, VST3 / AU, MFCC / spectral analysis fileciteturn1file0L17-L33\n\n---\n\n# Selected Projects\n\n## 1. VELA — Domain-Specialized LLM with Retrieval, Structured Reasoning, and Transparent Outputs\n**Qwen2.5-7B based | 2025 – Present**  \nHugging Face: `https://huggingface.co/intrect/VELA`\n\nBuilt a domain-specialized LLM system designed for high-context analytical tasks where a generic model tends to hallucinate or miss domain linkages. The focus was not only model performance, but also **trustworthy behavior**, **retrieval grounding**, and **transparent output generation**. fileciteturn1file0L57-L75\n\n### What I built\n- Fine-tuned a Qwen2.5-7B model on **36,713 SFT samples** and **24,779 DPO pairs**\n- Built retrieval infrastructure using **FAISS**, **KR-SBERT**, **BM25 / FTS5**, and structured search pipelines\n- Designed a reasoning workflow of **Think → Search → Analyze → Conclude**\n- Added reasoning traces and confidence-aware structured outputs to improve explainability\n- Built automatic 7-section analytical report generation\n- Quantized and deployed inference through **GGUF Q4/Q8**, **RunPod Serverless**, and **MLX**\n- Monitored domain drift and built incremental data collection to maintain output quality over time\n\n### Why it matters for Fieldguide\nThis project maps directly to enterprise agent work: retrieval-backed reasoning, structured outputs, explainability, confidence signaling, and continuous feedback loops for quality maintenance. It was built around the same core problem: how to make LLM outputs trustworthy enough for professional workflows. fileciteturn1file0L57-L75\n\n---\n\n## 2. STONKS — Agentic Workflow Platform for Complex Analytical Decisions\n**Solo full-stack build | 2024 – 2026**  \nDemo: `https://stonks.kimkate.net`\n\nBuilt a full-stack platform that automated a complex, multi-step analytical workflow involving search, retrieval, external APIs, scoring logic, and decision support. The system was designed around reducing cognitive load in environments where users would otherwise need to manually gather, compare, and validate fragmented information. fileciteturn1file0L76-L108\n\n### What I built\n- Implemented a **Claude API + GraphQL tool-calling agent workflow**\n- Integrated retrieval, sentiment analysis, structured scoring, classification, and real-time data into one operational loop\n- Built a **12-tab dashboard** and **42 modular API routers**\n- Added dynamic caching, real-time WebSocket streaming, and remote service access\n- Built feedback loops that tracked downstream outcomes and used them to improve scoring logic\n- Designed the system around **structured evidence collection**, **cross-validation**, and **decision support**, not just response generation\n\n### Scale / execution\n- **506,900 LOC**\n- **1,578 commits**\n- **2,400+ hours** of solo design, implementation, and iteration fileciteturn1file0L41-L56 fileciteturn1file0L76-L108\n\n### Why it matters for Fieldguide\nThis is the clearest example of my ability to convert a messy real-world workflow into discrete, testable agent behaviors. It also reflects how I think about production AI: retrieval, tooling, feedback loops, observability, and interfaces that help users trust outputs.\n\n---\n\n## 3. OpenSwarm — Multi-Agent Orchestrator for AI-Native Software Development\n**Open source**  \nGitHub: `https://github.com/unohee/OpenSwarm`\n\nBuilt a multi-agent orchestration system around Claude Code CLI to improve software development throughput and reduce context loss over long-running work. The system separates code generation and review into explicit agent roles and persists long-term context with vector memory. fileciteturn1file0L121-L126\n\n### What I built\n- Multi-instance orchestration for Claude Code CLI\n- Worker / Reviewer paired pipeline\n- LanceDB vector memory for long-term context persistence\n- Linear issue intake and Discord reporting integration\n\n### Outcome\n- **232 GitHub stars**\n- **20 forks**\n- Community validation after Hacker News exposure fileciteturn1file0L121-L126\n\n### Why it matters for Fieldguide\nThis project demonstrates AI-native engineering instincts in practice: using agents as core building blocks, structuring workflows around explicit roles and evaluations, and improving execution speed without sacrificing control.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Financial Data Pipeline — Retrieval-Ready Data Infrastructure for Large-Scale Analytical Systems\n**2024 – Present**  \nGitHub: `https://github.com/unohee/kis-agent`\n\nBuilt a large-scale data pipeline for collecting, cleaning, embedding, deduplicating, and serving structured and unstructured data for downstream analytical and LLM systems. This included noisy text corpora, multiple external APIs, and real-time market data infrastructure. fileciteturn1file0L127-L142\n\n### What I built\n- Multi-stage news ingestion and normalization pipeline\n- Embedding and retrieval-ready dataset generation\n- FastAPI services for real-time and historical data access\n- SQLite WAL sharding and parallelized processing\n- Open-source utilities for cleaning and semantic deduplication\n\n### Why it matters for Fieldguide\nFieldguide’s product depends on grounding AI in reliable workflows and retrieval. This project is direct evidence that I can build the data and retrieval backbone required for high-stakes AI systems.\n\n---\n\n## 5. ArtifactNet — AI-Generated Content Detection with Production Inference Support\nBuilt an AI-generated music detection system with near-SOTA performance, then packaged it for real-world inference through ONNX deployment and production-style serving workflows. fileciteturn1file0L41-L56\n\n### Why it matters for Fieldguide\nThis project strengthened the exact muscles required for professional AI products: evaluation design, signal validation, deployment, and defensible outputs in ambiguous problem spaces.\n\n---\n\n# What I Bring to Fieldguide\n\n## Agentic workflow design\nI have repeatedly built systems that decompose complex workflows into smaller units: retrieve evidence, call tools, score findings, generate structured outputs, and track quality. That is the core pattern behind enterprise AI agents.\n\n## Retrieval and explainability\nMy work consistently emphasizes retrieval-backed reasoning, transparent output structures, confidence signaling, and grounded generation rather than black-box response generation. That aligns closely with trust-heavy workflows like audit, assurance, and advisory. fileciteturn1file0L57-L75\n\n## Evaluation and feedback loops\nI design systems that improve through observed downstream outcomes, not just offline benchmarks. In practice, that has meant automated performance tracking, drift detection, and continuous adjustment of scoring or model behavior. fileciteturn1file0L90-L101\n\n## Production-minded execution\nI am comfortable building quickly, but I also spend real effort on packaging, deployment, monitoring, caching, and operational stability. I have deployed through RunPod Serverless, Cloudflare Tunnel, and lightweight production infrastructure that balances speed and reliability. fileciteturn1file0L17-L33\n\n## AI-native engineering instincts\nI use LLMs, agents, and automation as first-class engineering tools. OpenSwarm is the clearest public proof of that, but the same instinct runs through all of my work: structure ambiguity, automate what should be automated, keep humans in the loop where judgment matters.\n\n---\n\n# Additional Background\n\n- 10+ years of professional sound design experience, including work for Louis Vuitton and thisisneverthat\n- Experience teaching technical and creative subjects to non-engineering audiences\n- Comfortable working across Korean and English technical environments fileciteturn1file0L5-L10\n\n---\n\n**April 9, 2026**  \n**Heewon Oh**\n\n---\n\n이 버전은 원본보다 Fieldguide 쪽에 훨씬 맞다.  \n특히 다음을 의도적으로 바꿨다.\n\n- **finance alpha / Sharpe brag** → **complex workflow automation**\n- **trading product** → **agentic analytical system**\n- **model building** → **trustworthy enterprise AI behavior**\n- **solo hacker tone** → **production AI engineer tone**\n\n다음 단계로는 두 갈래가 맞다.\n\n1. **이걸 1-page resume 포맷으로 압축**\n2. **Fieldguide용 cover letter / intro paragraph 작성**\n\n개인적으로는 지금 단계에서 **resume 1페이지 압축본**이 먼저 필요하다."
